# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: openstreetmap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap is freely licensed under the Open Database License and is commonly used to make electronic maps, inform turn-by-turn navigation, and assist in humanitarian aid and data visualisation.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap uses its own data model to store geographical features which can then be exported into other GIS file formats.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The OpenStreetMap website itself is an online map, geodata search engine, and editor.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap was created by Steve Coast in response to the Ordnance Survey, the United Kingdom's national mapping agency, failing to release its data to the public under free licences in 2004.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Initially, maps in OSM were created only via GPS traces, but it was quickly populated by importing public domain geographical data such as the U.S.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] TIGER and by tracing imagery as permitted by source.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap's adoption was accelerated by the development of supporting software and applications and Google Maps' 2012 introduction of pricing.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The database is hosted by the OpenStreetMap Foundation, a non-profit organisation registered in England and Wales, and is funded mostly via donations.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Steve Coast founded the project in 2004 while attending University College London, initially focusing on mapping the United Kingdom.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In the UK and elsewhere, government-run and tax-funded projects like the Ordnance Survey created massive datasets but declined to freely and widely distribute them.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The first contribution was a street that Coast entered in December 2004 after cycling around Regent's Park in London with a GPS tracking unit.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In April 2006, the OpenStreetMap Foundation was established to encourage the growth, development and distribution of free geospatial data and provide geospatial data for anybody to use and share.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In April 2007, Automotive Navigation Data (AND) donated a complete road data set for the Netherlands and trunk road data for India and China to the project.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] By July 2007, when the first "State of the Map" (SotM) conference was held, there were 9,000 registered users.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In October 2007, OpenStreetMap completed the import of a US Census TIGER road dataset.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In December 2007, Oxford University became the first major organisation to use OpenStreetMap data on their main website.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Ways to import and export data have continued to grow – by 2008, the project developed tools to export OpenStreetMap data to power portable GPS units, replacing their existing proprietary and out-of-date maps.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In March 2008, two founders of CloudMade, a commercial company that uses OpenStreetMap data, announced that they had received venture capital funding of €2.4 million.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2010, AOL launched an OSM-based version of MapQuest and committed $1 million to increasing OSM's coverage of local communities for its Patch website.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2012, the launch of pricing for Google Maps led several prominent websites to switch from their service to OpenStreetMap and other competitors.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Chief among these were Foursquare and Craigslist, which adopted OpenStreetMap, and Apple, which ended a contract with Google and launched a self-built mapping platform using TomTom and OpenStreetMap data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As of 2025, TomTom, Microsoft, Esri and Meta are the highest-tier corporate sponsors of the OpenStreetMap Foundation.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The OSM project aims to collect data about stationary objects throughout the world, including infrastructure and other aspects of the built environment, points of interest, land use and cover classifications, and topography.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Map features range in scale from international boundaries to hyperlocal details such as shops and street furniture.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Although historically significant features and ongoing construction projects are routinely included in the database, the project's scope is limited to the present day, as opposed to the past or future.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM's data model differs markedly from that of a conventional GIS or CAD system.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] It is a topological data structure without the formal concept of a layer, allowing thematically diverse data to commingle and interconnect.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The OpenStreetMap data primitives are stored and processed in different formats.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap server uses PostgreSQL database, with one table for each data primitive, with individual objects stored as rows.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The data structure is defined as part of the OSM API.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The current version of the API, v0.6, was released in 2009.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A 2023 study found that this version's changes to the relation data structure had the effect of reducing the total number of relations; however, it simultaneously lowered the barrier to creating new relations and spurred the application of relations to new use cases.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Each element contains key–value pairs, called *tags*, that identify and describe the feature.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A recommended ontology of map features (the meaning of *tags*) is maintained on a wiki.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] New tagging schemes can always be proposed by a popular vote of a written proposal in OpenStreetMap wiki, however, there is no requirement to follow this process: editors are free to use any tags they like to describe a feature.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] There are over 89 million different kinds of tags in use as of June 2017.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap data has been favourably compared with proprietary datasources, although as of 2009 data quality varied across the world.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A study in 2011 compared OSM data with TomTom for Germany.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] For car navigation TomTom has 9% more information, while for the entire street network, OSM has 27% more information.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2011, TriMet, which serves the Portland, Oregon, metropolitan area, found that OSM's street data, consumed through the routing engine OpenTripPlanner and the search engine Apache Solr, yields better results than analogous GIS datasets managed by local government agencies.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A 2021 study compared the *OpenStreetMap Carto* style's symbology to that of the Soviet Union's comprehensive military mapping programme, finding that OSM matched the Soviet maps in coverage of some features such as road infrastructure but gave less prominence to the natural environment.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A study from 2021 found the mean completeness of shop data in the German regions Baden-Württemberg and Saxony to be 88% and 82% respectively.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Instead of comparing OSM data to other datasets, the authors looked at how the number of shops developed over time.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] They then determined the expected number of shops by estimating the saturation level.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] According to a 2024 study using PyPSA, OSM has the most detailed and up-to-date publicly available coverage of the European high-voltage electrical grid, comparable to official data from the European Network of Transmission System Operators for Electricity.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] All data added to the project needs to have a licence compatible with the Open Data Commons Open Database Licence (ODbL).
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] This can include out-of-copyright information, public domain or other licences.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Software used in the production and presentation of OpenStreetMap data may have separate licensing terms.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap data and derived tiles were originally published under the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike licence (CC BY-SA) with the intention of promoting free use and redistribution of the data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In September 2012, the licence was changed to the ODbL in order to define its bearing on data rather than representation more specifically.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As part of this relicensing process, some of the map data was removed from the public distribution.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] This included all data contributed by members that did not agree to the new licensing terms, as well as all subsequent edits to those affected objects.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] It also included any data contributed based on input data that was not compatible with the new terms.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Estimates suggested that over 97% of data would be retained globally, but certain regions would be affected more than others, such as in Australia where 24 to 84% of objects would be retained, depending on the type of object.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Ultimately, more than 99% of the data was retained, with Australia and Poland being the countries most severely affected by the change.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The license change and resulting deletions prompted a group of dissenting mappers to establish Free Open Street Map (FOSM), a fork of OSM that remained under the previous license.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Map tiles provided by the OpenStreetMap project were licensed under CC-BY-SA-2.0 until 1 August 2020.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The ODbL license requires attribution to be attached to maps produced from OpenStreetMap data, but does not require that any particular license be applied to those maps.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] "©OpenStreetMap Contributors" with link to ODbL copyright page as attribution requirement is used on the site.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM publishes official database dumps of the entire "planet" for reuse on minutely and weekly intervals, formatted as XML or binary Protocol Buffers.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Alternative third-party distributions provide access to OSM data in other formats or to more manageable subsets of the data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Geofabrik publishes extracts of the database in OSM and shapefile formats for individual countries and political subdivisions.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Amazon Web Services publishes the planet on S3 for querying in Athena.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As part of the QLever project, the University of Freiburg publishes Turtle dumps suitable for linked data systems.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] From 2020 to 2024, Meta published the Daylight Map Distribution, which applied quality assurance processes and added some external datasets to OSM data to make it more production-ready.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM data also forms a major part of the Overture Maps Foundation's dataset and commercial datasets from Mapbox and MapTiler.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Map data is collected by ground survey, personal knowledge, digitizing from imagery, and government data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Ground survey data is collected by volunteers traditionally using tools such as a handheld GPS unit, a notebook, digital camera and voice recorder.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Software applications on smartphones (mobile devices) have made it easy for anybody to survey.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The data is then entered into the OpenStreetMap database using a number of software tools including JOSM, Potlatch, and Merkaator.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Additionally, more recently apps such as StreetComplete offer "quests" to users in nearby vicinity, allowing them to add metadata to specific points of interest (such as, for example, the opening hours of a restaurant or whether or not a particular crosswalk has tactile paving).
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Mapathon competition events are also held by local OpenStreetMap teams and by non-profit organisations and local governments to map a particular area.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The availability of aerial photography and other data from commercial and government sources has added important sources of data for manual editing and automated imports.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Special processes are in place to handle automated imports and avoid legal and technical problems.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Ground surveys are performed by a mapper, on foot, bicycle, or in a car, motorcycle, or boat.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Map data is typically recorded on a GPS unit or on a smart phone with mapping app; a common file format is GPX.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Once the data has been collected, it is entered into the database by uploading it onto the project's website together with appropriate attribute data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As collecting and uploading data may be separated from editing objects, contribution to the project is possible without using a GPS unit, such as by using paper mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Similar to users contributing data using a GPS unit, corporations (e.g.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Amazon) with large vehicle fleets may use telemetry data from the vehicles to contribute data to OpenStreetMap.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Some committed contributors adopt the task of mapping whole towns and cities, or organising mapping parties to gather the support of others to complete a map area.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A large number of less-active users contributes corrections and small additions to the map.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Maxar, Bing, ESRI, and Mapbox are some of the providers of aerial/satellite imagery which are used as a backdrop for map production.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] (2006–2011), Bing (2010 – present), and DigitalGlobe (2017–2023) allowed their aerial photography, satellite imagery to be used as a backdrop for map production.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] For a period from 2009 to 2011, NearMap Pty Ltd made their high-resolution PhotoMaps (of major Australian cities, plus some rural Australian areas) available under a CC BY-SA licence.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Data from several street-level image platforms are available as map data photo overlays.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Bing Streetside 360° image tracks, and the open and crowdsourced Mapillary and KartaView platforms provide generally smartphone and dashcam images.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Additionally, a Mapillary traffic sign data layer, a product of user-submitted images is also available.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Some government agencies have released official data on appropriate licences.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] This includes the United States, where works of the federal government are placed under public domain.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In the United States, most roads originate from TIGER from the Census Bureau.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Geographic names were initially sourced from Geographic Names Information System, and some areas contain water features from the National Hydrography Dataset.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In the UK, some Ordnance Survey OpenData is imported.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In Canada Natural Resources Canada's CanVec vector data and GeoBase provide landcover and streets.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Globally, OpenStreetMap initially used the prototype global shoreline from NOAA.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Due to it being oversimplified and crude, it has been mainly replaced by other government sources or manual tracing.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Out-of-copyright maps can be good sources of information about features that do not change frequently.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Copyright periods vary, but in the UK Crown copyright expires after 50 years and hence old Ordnance Survey maps can legally be used.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A complete set of UK 1 inch/mile maps from the late 1940s and early 1950s has been collected, scanned, and is available online as a resource for contributors.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The map data can be edited from a number of editing applications that provide aids including satellite and aerial imagery, street-level imagery, GPS traces, and photo and voice annotations.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] By default, the official OSM website directs contributors to the Web-based iD editor.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Meta developed a fork of this editor, Rapid, that provides access to external datasets, including some derived from machine learning detections.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] For complex or large-scale changes, experienced users often turn to more powerful desktop editing applications such as JOSM and Potlatch.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Several mobile applications also edit OSM.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Go Map!! and Vespucci are the primary full-featured editors for iOS and Android, respectively.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] StreetComplete is an Android application designed for laypeople around a guided question-and-answer format.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] CoMaps, Every Door, Maps.me, Organic Maps, and OsmAnd include basic functionality for editing points of interest.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Between 2018 and 2023, the top five editing tools by number of edits were JOSM, iD, StreetComplete, Rapid, and Potlatch.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM accepts contributions from the general public.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Changesets submitted through editors and the OSM API immediately enter the database and are quickly published for reuse, without going through peer review beforehand.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The API only validates changes for basic well-formedness, but not for topological or logical consistency or for adherence to community norms.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As a crowdsourced project, OSM is susceptible to several forms of data vandalism, including copyright infringement, graffiti, and spam.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Overall, vandalism accounts for an estimated 0.2% of edits to OSM, which is relatively low compared to vandalism on Wikipedia.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Members of the community detect and fix most unintentional errors and vandalism promptly, by monitoring the slippy map and revision history on the main website, as well as by searching for issues using tools like OSMCha, OSM Inspector, and Osmose.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In addition to community vigilance, the OpenStreetMap Foundation's Data Working Group and a group of administrators are responsible for responding to vandals.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As of 2022, a comprehensive security assessment of the OSM data model has yet to take place.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Players of *Pokémon Go* have been known to vandalize OSM, one of the game's map data sources, to manipulate gameplay.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] However, this vandalism is casual, rarely sustained, and it is predictable based on the mechanics of the game.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The project has a geographically diverse user-base, due to emphasis of local knowledge and "on-the-ground" situation in the process of data collection.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Many early contributors were cyclists who survey with and for other cyclists, charting cycleroutes and navigable trails.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Contributors are predominately men, with only 3–5% being women.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] By August 2008, shortly after the second The State of the Map conference was held, there were over 50,000 registered contributors; by March 2009, there were 100,000 and by the end of 2009 the figure was nearly 200,000.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In April 2012, OpenStreetMap cleared 600,000 registered contributors.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] On 6 January 2013, OpenStreetMap reached one million registered users.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Around 30% of users have contributed at least one point to the OpenStreetMap database.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] As per a study conducted in 2011, only 38% of members carried out at least one edit and only 5% of members created more than 1000 nodes.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] According to another study, when a competing maps platform is launched, OSM attracts fewer new contributors and pre-existing contributors increase their level of contribution possibly driven by their ideological attachment to the platform.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Overall, there is a negative effect on the quantum of contributions.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Some companies freely license satellite/aerial/street imagery sources from which OpenStreetMap contributors trace roads and features, while other companies make data available for importing map data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Automotive Navigation Data (AND) provided a complete road data set for Netherlands and trunk roads data for China and India.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Amazon Logistics uses OpenStreetMap for navigation and has a team which revises the map based on GPS traces and feedback from its drivers.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In eight Southeast Asian countries, Grab has contributed more than 800,000 kilometres (500,000 mi) of roads based on drivers' GPS traces, including many narrow alleyways that are missing from other mapping platforms. eCourier also contributes its drivers' GPS traces to OSM.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] According to a study, about 17% of road kilometers were last touched by corporate teams in March 2020.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The top 13 corporate contributors during 2014–2020 include Apple, Kaart, Amazon, Facebook, Mapbox, Digital Egypt, Grab, Microsoft, Telenav, Developmentseed, Uber, Lightcyphers and Lyft.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] According to OpenStreetMap Statistics, the over all percentage of edits from corporations peaked at about 10% in 2020 and 2021 and has since fallen to about 2-3% in 2024.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Humanitarian OpenStreetMap Team (HOT) is a nonprofit organisation promoting community mapping across the world.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] It developed the open source HOT Tasking Manager for collaboration, and contributed to mapping efforts after the April 2015 Nepal earthquake, the 2016 Kumamoto earthquakes, and the 2016 Ecuador earthquake.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The Missing Maps Project, founded by the American Red Cross, Doctors Without Borders, and other NGOs, uses HOT Tasking Manager.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The University of Heidelberg hosts the Disastermappers Project for training university students in mapping for humanitarian purposes.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] When Ebola broke out in 2014, the volunteers mapped 100,000 buildings and hundreds of miles of roads in Guinea in just five days.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Local groups such as Ramani Huria in Dar es Salaam incorporate OSM mapping into their community resilience programmes.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Community emergency response teams in San Francisco and elsewhere organize field surveys and mapathons to contribute information about fire alarm call boxes, hazard symbols, and other relevant features.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Since 2007, the OpenStreetMap community has organised State of the Map (SotM), an annual international conference at which stakeholders present on technical progress and discuss policy issues.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The conference is held each year in a different city around the world.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Various regional editions of State of the Map are also held for each continent, regions such as the Baltics and Latin America, and some countries with especially active local communities, such as France, Germany, and the United States.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetmap's community has been criticised by a former moderator and long-time contributor, Serge Wroclawski, due to the fact that while it appears like a map, it functions like a database.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] He also noted that the community was not welcoming to new mappers, where there is no review model, and so if bad edits are removed the original contributor may not know why, as well as noting that the project has hidden gatekeepers who resist change.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The official OSM website at openstreetmap.org is the project's main hub for contributors.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A reference implementation of a slippy map (featuring a selection of third-party tile layers), a revision log, and integrations with basic geocoders and route planners facilitate the community's management of the database contents.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Logged-in users can access an embedded copy of the iD editor and shortcuts for desktop editors for contributing to the database, as well as some rudimentary social networking features such as user profiles and diaries.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The website's built-in REST API and OAuth authentication enable third-party applications to programmatically interact with the site's major functionality, including submitting changes.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Much of the website runs as a Ruby on Rails application backed by a PostgreSQL database.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Strictly speaking, the OSM project produces only a geographic database, leaving data consumers to handle every aspect of postprocessing the data and presenting it to end users.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] However, a large ecosystem of command line tools, software libraries, and cloud services has developed around OSM, much of it as free and open-source software.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Two kinds of software stacks have emerged for rendering OSM data as an interactive slippy map.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In one, a server-side rendering engine such as Mapnik prerenders the data as a series of raster image tiles, then serves them using a library such as *mod_tile*.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A library such as OpenLayers or Leaflet displays these tiles on the client side on the slippy map.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Alternatively, a server application converts raw OSM data into vector tiles according to a schema, such as Mapbox Streets, OpenMapTiles, or Shortbread.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] These tiles are rendered on the client side by a library such as the Mapbox Maps SDK, MapLibre, Mapzen's Tangrams, or OpenLayers.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Applications such as Mapbox Studio allow designers to author vector styles in an interactive, visual environment.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Vector maps are especially common among three-dimensional mapping applications and mobile applications.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Plugins are available for embedding slippy maps in content management systems such as WordPress.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A geocoder indexes map data so that users can search it by name and address (geocoding) or look up an address based on a given coordinate pair (reverse geocoding).
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Several geocoders are designed to index OSM data, including Nominatim (from the Latin, 'by name'), which is built into the official OSM website along with GeoNames.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Komoot's Photon search engine provides incremental search functionality based on a Nominatim database.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The nonprofit Social Web Foundation's places.pub formats OSM locations as ActivityPub objects, enabling social media applications to enrich geocodes associated with check-ins.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Element 84's natural language geocoder uses a large language model to identify OSM geometries to return.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A variety of route planning libraries and services are based on OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM's official website has featured GraphHopper, the Open Source Routing Machine, and Valhalla since February 2015.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Other widely deployed routing engines include Openrouteservice and OpenTripPlanner, which specializes in public transport routing.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM is an important source of geographic data in many fields, including transportation, analysis, public services, and humanitarian aid.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] However, much of its use by consumers is indirect via third-party products, because customer reviews and aerial and satellite imagery are not part of the project per se.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A variety of applications and services allow users to visualise OSM data in the form of a map.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The official OSM website features an interactive slippy map interface so that users can efficiently edit maps and view changesets.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] It presents the general-purpose *OpenStreetMap Carto* style alongside a selection of specialised styles for cycling and public transport.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Beyond this reference implementation, community-maintained map applications focus on alternative cartographic representations and specialised use cases.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] For example, OpenRailwayMap is a detailed online map of the world's railway infrastructure based on OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenSeaMap is a world nautical chart built as a mashup of OpenStreetMap, crowdsourced water depth tracks, and third-party weather and bathymetric data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenTopoMap uses OSM and SRTM data to create topographic maps.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Tactile Map Automated Production prints tactile maps that feature embossed streets, paths, and railroads from OSM.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] On the desktop, applications such as GNOME Maps and Marble provide their own interactive styles.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] GIS suites such as QGIS allow users to produce their own custom maps based on the same data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Many commercial and noncommercial websites feature maps powered by OSM data in locator maps, store locators, infographics, story maps, and other mashups.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Locator maps on Wikipedia and Wikivoyage articles for cities and points of interest are powered by a MediaWiki extension and the OSM-based Wikimedia Maps service.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The locator maps on Craigslist, Facebook, Flickr, Foursquare City Guide, Gurtam's Wialon, and Snapchat are also powered by OSM.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] From 2013 to 2022, GitHub visualized any uploaded GeoJSON data atop an OSM-based Mapbox basemap.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2012, Apple quietly switched the locator map in iPhoto from Google Maps to OSM.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Interactive OSM-based maps appear in many augmented reality games, mobile navigation applications, and fitness applications, such as Strava.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The Overpass API searches the OSM database for features whose metadata or topology match criteria specified in a structured query language.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Overpass turbo is an integrated development environment for querying this API.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Bellingcat develops an alternative Overpass frontend for geolocating photographs.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] QLever and Sophox are triplestores that accept standard SPARQL queries to return facts about the OSM database.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Geographic information retrieval systems such as NLMaps Web and OSCAR answer natural language queries based on OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSMnx is a Python package for analysing and visualising the OSM road network.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM is often a source for realistic, large-scale transport network analyses because the raw road network data is freely available or because of aspects of coverage that are uncommon in proprietary alternatives.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM data can be imported into professional-grade traffic simulation frameworks such as Aimsun Next, Eclipse SUMO, and MATSim, as well as urban planning–focused simulators such as A/B Street.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A team at the Virginia Tech Transportation Institute has used Valhalla's map matching function to evaluate advanced driver-assistance systems.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The United States Census Bureau has analysed routes generated by the Open Source Routing Machine along with American Community Survey data to develop a socioeconomic profile of commuters affected by the Francis Scott Key Bridge collapse.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM is also used in conservation and land-use planning research.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The annual Forest Landscape Integrity Index is based on a comprehensive map of remaining roadless areas derived from OSM's road network.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Computer vision researchers have trained convolutional neural networks on OSM's land use areas to perform feature detection and image segmentation on Sentinel-2 satellite imagery, both globally (OpenSentinelMap) and in Europe (OSMlanduse).
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Some newsrooms routinely incorporate OSM data into their workflows and data journalism projects.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The *Chicago Tribune* maintains a dashboard of crime in Chicago visualized against an OSM basemap.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] *The Washington Post* and *Los Angeles Times* accompany articles with locator maps and more in-depth visuals that rely on OSM's hyperlocal coverage of places that have less detail in proprietary maps.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Various groups, including researchers, data journalists, the Open Knowledge Foundation, and Geochicas, have used OSM in conjunction with Wikidata to explore the demographics of people honoured by street names and raise awareness of gender bias in naming decisions.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM is a data source for some Web-based map services.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2010, Bing Maps introduced an option to display an OSM-based map and later began including building data from OSM by default.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Wheelmap.org is a portal for discovering wheelchair-accessible places, mashing up OSM data with a separate, crowdsourced customer review database.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Mobile applications such as CoMaps, CycleStreets, Karta GPS, Komoot, Locus Map, Maps.me, Organic Maps, and OsmAnd also provide offline route planning capabilities.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Apple Maps uses OSM data in many countries.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Some of Garmin's GPS products incorporate OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM is a popular source for road data among Iranian navigation applications, such as Balad.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Geotab and TeleNav also use OSM data in their in-car navigation systems.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Some public transportation providers rely on OpenStreetMap data in their route planning services and for other analysis needs.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM data appears in the driver or rider application or powers backend operations for ridesharing companies and related services.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2022, Grab completed a migration from Google Maps and Here Maps to an in-house, OSM-based navigation solution, reducing trip times by about 90 seconds.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2024, Ola introduced a mapping platform partly based on OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2019, owners of Tesla cars found that the Smart Summon automatic valet parking feature within Tesla Autopilot relied on OSM's coverage of parking lot details.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Webots uses OSM data to simulate realistic surroundings for autonomous vehicles.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Humanitarian aid agencies use OSM data both proactively and reactively.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM's road and building coverage allow them to discover patterns of disease outbreaks and target interventions such as antimalarial medications toward remote villages.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] After a disaster occurs, they produce large-format printed maps and downloadable maps for GPS tracking units for aid workers to use in the field.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The 2010 Haiti earthquake established a model for non-governmental organisations (NGOs) to collaborate with international organisations.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenStreetMap and Crisis Commons volunteers used available satellite imagery to map the roads, buildings and refugee camps of Port-au-Prince in just two days, building "the most complete digital map of Haiti's roads".
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The resulting data and maps have been used by several organisations providing relief aid, such as the World Bank, the European Commission Joint Research Centre, the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, UNOSAT and others.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] After Haiti, the OpenStreetMap community continued mapping to support humanitarian organisations for various crises and disasters.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OSM is a map data source for many location-based games that require broad coverage of local details such as streets and buildings.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] One of the earliest such games was Hasbro's short-lived *Monopoly City Streets* (2009), which offered a choice between OSM and Google Maps as the playing board.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] *Battlefield 4* (2013) used a customized OSM-based Mapbox map in its leaderboards.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2013, Ballardia shut down testing of *World of the Living Dead: Resurrection*, because too many players attempted to use the Google Maps–based game, then relaunched it after switching to OSM, which could handle thousands of players.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Flight simulators combine OSM's coverage of roads and structures with other sources of natural environment data, acting as sophisticated 3D map renderers, in order to add realism to the ground below.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] *X-Plane 10* (2011) replaced TIGER and VMAP0 with OSM for roads, railways, and some bodies of water.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] *Microsoft Flight Simulator* (2020) introduced software-generated building models based in part on OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2020, *FlightGear Flight Simulator* officially integrated OSM buildings and roads into the official scenery.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] City-building games and business simulation games use a subset of OSM data as a base layer to take advantage of the player's familiarity with their surroundings.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In *NIMBY Rails* (2021), the player develops a railway network that coexists with real-world roads and bodies of water.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In Jutsu Games' *Infection Free Zone* (2024), the player builds fortifications amid a post-apocalyptic world based on OSM streets and buildings.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Other titles include *City Bus Manager*, *Global Farmer*, and *Logistical: Earth*.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] These games incorporate realistic elements but take some liberties to enhance gameplay and mitigate gaps in OSM's coverage.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Alternate reality games rely on OSM data to determine where rewards and other elements of the game spawn in the player's presence, such as the 'portals' in *Ingress*, the 'PokéStops' and 'Pokémon Gyms' in *Pokémon Go*, and the 'tappables' in *Minecraft Earth* (2019).
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2017, when Niantic migrated its augmented reality titles, including *Ingress* and *Pokémon Go*, from Google Maps to OSM, the overworld maps in these games initially became more detailed for some players but completely blank for others, due to OSM's uneven geographic coverage at the time.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In the first six weeks after launching in South Korea, *Pokémon Go* produced a seventeenfold spike in daily OSM contributions within the country.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] In 2024, Niantic migrated its titles to Overture Maps data, which incorporates some OSM data.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] According to the Open Data Institute, OSM is one of the most successful collaboratively maintained open datasets in existence.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] A 2020 research report by Accenture estimated the total replacement value of the OSM database, the value of OSM software development effort, and maintenance overhead at $1.67 billion, roughly equivalent to the value of the Linux kernel in 2008.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Several startups have turned OSM-based software as a service into a business model, including Carto, Mapbox, MapTiler, and Mapzen.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The Overture Maps Foundation incorporates OSM data in some of its GIS layers.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] Several open collaborative mapping projects are modeled after OSM and rely on OSM software.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenHistoricalMap is a world historical map that tracks the evolution of human geography over time, from prehistory to the present day.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] OpenGeofiction focuses on fantasy cartography and worldbuilding.
[src:openstreetmap/openstreetmap] The OSM community sees these projects as complements for aspects of geography that are out of scope for OSM.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In information systems, a **tag** is a keyword or term assigned to a piece of information (such as an Internet bookmark, multimedia, database record, or computer file).
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] This kind of metadata helps describe an item and allows it to be found again by browsing or searching.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Tags are generally chosen informally and personally by the item's creator or by its viewer, depending on the system, although they may also be chosen from a controlled vocabulary.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Tagging was popularized by websites associated with Web 2.0 and is an important feature of many Web 2.0 services.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] It is now also part of other database systems, desktop applications, and operating systems.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] People use tags to aid classification, mark ownership, note boundaries, and indicate online identity.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Tags may take the form of words, images, or other identifying marks.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] An analogous example of tags in the physical world is museum object tagging.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] People were using textual keywords to classify information and objects long before computers.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Computer based search algorithms made the use of such keywords a rapid way of exploring records.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Tagging gained popularity due to the growth of social bookmarking, image sharing, and social networking websites.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] These sites allow users to create and manage labels (or "tags") that categorize content using simple keywords.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Websites that include tags often display collections of tags as tag clouds, as do some desktop applications.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] On websites that aggregate the tags of all users, an individual user's tags can be useful both to them and to the larger community of the website's users.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Tagging systems have sometimes been classified into two kinds: *top-down* and *bottom-up*.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Top-down taxonomies are created by an authorized group of designers (sometimes in the form of a controlled vocabulary), whereas bottom-up taxonomies (called folksonomies) are created by all users.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Some researchers and applications have experimented with combining hierarchical and non-hierarchical tagging to aid in information retrieval.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Others are combining top-down and bottom-up tagging, including in some large library catalogs (OPACs) such as WorldCat.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] When tags or other taxonomies have further properties (or semantics) such as relationships and attributes, they constitute an ontology.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In folder system a file cannot exist in two or more folders so tag system has been thought more convenient.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] But transitioning to tag system requires awareness of difference between properties of two systems.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In folder system the information of classification is put outside of the file and we can change folder at once.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In tag system the information of classification is put inside the file so changing its tag means changing the file and it needs to be saved again and takes time.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Metadata tags as described in this article should not be confused with the use of the word "tag" in some software to refer to an automatically generated cross-reference; examples of the latter are *tags tables* in Emacs and *smart tags* in Microsoft Office.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] The use of keywords as part of an identification and classification system long predates computers.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Paper data storage devices, notably edge-notched cards, that permitted classification and sorting by multiple criteria were already in use prior to the twentieth century, and faceted classification has been used by libraries since the 1930s.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, Emacs, the text editor for Unix systems, offered a companion software program called *Tags* that could automatically build a table of cross-references called a *tags table* that Emacs could use to jump between a function call and that function's definition.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] This use of the word "tag" did not refer to metadata tags, but was an early use of the word "tag" in software to refer to a word index.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Online databases and early websites deployed keyword tags as a way for publishers to help users find content.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In the early days of the World Wide Web, the `keywords` meta element was used by web designers to tell web search engines what the web page was about, but these keywords were only visible in a web page's source code and were not modifiable by users.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In 1997, the collaborative portal "A Description of the Equator and Some ØtherLands" produced by documenta X, Germany, used the folksonomic term *Tag* for its co-authors and guest authors on its Upload page.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In "The Equator" the term *Tag* for user-input was described as an *abstract literal or keyword* to aid the user.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] However, users defined singular *Tags*, and did not share *Tags* at that point.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In 2003, the social bookmarking website Delicious provided a way for its users to add "tags" to their bookmarks (as a way to help find them later); Delicious also provided browseable aggregated views of the bookmarks of all users featuring a particular tag.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Within a couple of years, the photo sharing website Flickr allowed its users to add their own text tags to each of their pictures, constructing flexible and easy metadata that made the pictures highly searchable.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] The success of Flickr and the influence of Delicious popularized the concept, and other social software websites—such as YouTube, Technorati, and Last.fm—also implemented tagging.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In 2005, the Atom web syndication standard provided a "category" element for inserting subject categories into web feeds, and in 2007 Tim Bray proposed a "tag" URN.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Many systems (and other web content management systems) allow authors to add free-form tags to a post, along with (or instead of) placing the post into a predetermined category.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] For example, a post may display that it has been tagged with `baseball` and `tickets`.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Each of those tags is usually a web link leading to an index page listing all of the posts associated with that tag.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] The blog may have a sidebar listing all the tags in use on that blog, with each tag leading to an index page.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] To reclassify a post, an author edits its list of tags.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] All connections between posts are automatically tracked and updated by the blog software; there is no need to relocate the page within a complex hierarchy of categories.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Some desktop applications and web applications feature their own tagging systems, such as email tagging in Gmail and Mozilla Thunderbird, bookmark tagging in Firefox, audio tagging in iTunes or Winamp, and photo tagging in various applications.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Some of these applications display collections of tags as tag clouds.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] There are various systems for applying tags to the files in a computer's file system.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In Apple's Mac System 7, released in 1991, users could assign one of seven editable colored labels (with editable names such as "Essential", "Hot", and "In Progress") to each file and folder.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In later iterations of the Mac operating system ever since OS X 10.9 was released in 2013, users could assign multiple arbitrary tags as extended file attributes to any file or folder, and before that time the open-source OpenMeta standard provided similar tagging functionality for Mac OS X.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Several semantic file systems that implement tags are available for the Linux kernel, including Tagsistant.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Microsoft Windows allows users to set tags only on Microsoft Office documents and some kinds of picture files.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Cross-platform file tagging standards include Extensible Metadata Platform (XMP), an ISO standard for embedding metadata into popular image, video and document file formats, such as JPEG and PDF, without breaking their readability by applications that do not support XMP.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] XMP largely supersedes the earlier IPTC Information Interchange Model.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Exif is a standard that specifies the image and audio file formats used by digital cameras, including some metadata tags.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] TagSpaces is an open-source cross-platform application for tagging files; it inserts tags into the filename.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] An *official tag* is a keyword adopted by events and conferences for participants to use in their web publications, such as blog entries, photos of the event, and presentation slides.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Search engines can then index them to make relevant materials related to the event searchable in a uniform way.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In this case, the tag is part of a controlled vocabulary.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] A researcher may work with a large collection of items (e.g. press quotes, a bibliography, images) in digital form.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] If he/she wishes to associate each with a small number of themes (e.g. to chapters of a book, or to sub-themes of the overall subject), then a group of tags for these themes can be attached to each of the items in the larger collection.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In this way, freeform classification allows the author to manage what would otherwise be unwieldy amounts of information.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] A **triple tag** or **machine tag** uses a special syntax to define extra semantic information about the tag, making it easier or more meaningful for interpretation by a computer program.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Triple tags comprise three parts: a namespace, a predicate, and a value.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] For example, `geo:long=50.123456` is a tag for the geographical longitude coordinate whose value is 50.123456.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] This triple structure is similar to the Resource Description Framework model for information.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] The triple tag format was first devised for geolicious in November 2004, to map Delicious bookmarks, and gained wider acceptance after its adoption by Mappr and GeoBloggers to map Flickr photos.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In January 2007, Aaron Straup Cope at Flickr introduced the term *machine tag* as an alternative name for the triple tag, adding some questions and answers on purpose, syntax, and use.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Specialized metadata for geographical identification is known as *geotagging*; machine tags are also used for other purposes, such as identifying photos taken at a specific event or naming species using binomial nomenclature.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] A hashtag is a kind of metadata tag marked by the prefix `#`, sometimes known as a "hash" symbol.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] This form of tagging is used on microblogging and social networking services such as Twitter, Facebook, Google+, VK and Instagram.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] The hash is used to distinguish tag text, as distinct, from other text in the post.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] A **knowledge tag** is a type of meta-information that describes or defines some aspect of a piece of information (such as a document, digital image, database table, or web page).
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] These tag profiles reference an information resource that resides in a distributed, and often heterogeneous, storage repository.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Knowledge tags are part of a knowledge management discipline that leverages Enterprise 2.0 methodologies for users to capture insights, expertise, attributes, dependencies, or relationships associated with a data resource.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] These forms of knowledge often exist outside the data itself and are derived from personal experience, insight, or expertise.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Knowledge tags are considered an expansion of the information itself that adds additional value, context, and meaning to the information.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In a typical tagging system, there is no explicit information about the meaning or semantics of each tag, and a user can apply new tags to an item as easily as applying older tags.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] For example, the tag "orange" may refer to the fruit or the color, and items related to a version of the Linux kernel may be tagged "Linux", "kernel", "Penguin", "software", or a variety of other terms.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Users can also choose tags that are different inflections of words (such as singular and plural), which can contribute to navigation difficulties if the system does not include stemming of tags when searching or browsing.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Larger-scale folksonomies address some of the problems of tagging, in that users of tagging systems tend to notice the current use of "tag terms" within these systems, and thus use existing tags in order to easily form connections to related items.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In this way, folksonomies may collectively develop a partial set of tagging conventions.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Despite the apparent lack of control, research has shown that a simple form of shared vocabulary emerges in social bookmarking systems.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Collaborative tagging exhibits a form of complex systems dynamics (or self-organizing dynamics).
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Thus, even if no central controlled vocabulary constrains the actions of individual users, the distribution of tags converges over time to stable power law distributions.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Once such stable distributions form, simple folksonomic vocabularies can be extracted by examining the correlations that form between different tags.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] In addition, research has suggested that it is easier for machine learning algorithms to learn tag semantics when users tag "verbosely"—when they annotate resources with a wealth of freely associated, descriptive keywords.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Tagging systems open to the public are also open to tag spam, in which people apply an excessive number of tags or unrelated tags to an item (such as a YouTube video) in order to attract viewers.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] This abuse can be mitigated using human or statistical identification of spam items.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] The number of tags allowed may also be limited to reduce spam.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Some tagging systems provide a single text box to enter tags, so to be able to tokenize the string, a separator must be used.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Two popular separators are the space character and the comma.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] To enable the use of separators in the tags, a system may allow for higher-level separators (such as quotation marks) or escape characters.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] Systems can avoid the use of separators by allowing only one tag to be added to each input widget at a time, although this makes adding multiple tags more time-consuming.
[src:openstreetmap/tag-metadata] A syntax for use within HTML is to use the **rel-tag** microformat which uses the *rel* attribute with value "tag" (i.e., `rel="tag"`) to indicate that the linked-to page acts as a tag for the current context.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] VGI can be seen as an extension of critical and participatory approaches to geographic information systems.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Some examples of this phenomenon are WikiMapia, OpenStreetMap, and Yandex.Map editor.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] These sites provide general base map information and allow users to create their own content by marking locations where various events occurred or certain features exist, but aren't already shown on the base map.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Other examples include 311-style request systems and 3D spatial technology.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Additionally, VGI commonly populates the content offered through location-based services such as the restaurant review site Yelp.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] One of the most important elements of VGI in contrast to standard user-generated content is the geographic element, and its relationship with collaborative mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] The information volunteered by the individual is linked to a specific geographic region.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] While this is often taken to relate to elements of traditional cartography, VGI offers the possibility of including subjective, emotional, or other non-cartographic information.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Geo-referenced data produced within services such as Trip Advisor, Flickr, Twitter, Instagram and Panoramio can be considered as VGI.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] VGI has attracted concerns about data quality, and specifically about its credibility and the possibility of vandalism.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] The term VGI has been criticized for poorly representing common variations in the data of OpenStreetMap and other sites: that some of the data is paid, in the case of CloudMade's ambassadors, or generated by another entity, as in US Census data.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Because it is gathered by individuals with no formal training, the quality and reliability of VGI is a topic of much debate.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Some methods of quality assurance have been tested, namely, the use of control data to verify VGI accuracy.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] While there is concern over the authority of the data, VGI may provide benefits beyond that of professional geographic information (PGI), partly due to its ability to collect and present data not collected or curated by traditional/professional sources.
[src:openstreetmap/volunteered-geographic-information] Additionally, VGI provides positive emotional value to users in functionality, satisfaction, social connection and ethics.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The advent of web mapping can be regarded as a major new trend in cartography.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Until recently, cartography was restricted to a few companies, institutes and mapping agencies, requiring relatively expensive and complex hardware and software as well as skilled cartographers and geomatics engineers.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping has brought many geographical datasets, including free ones generated by OpenStreetMap and proprietary datasets owned by Baidu, Google, HERE, TomTom, and others.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] A range of free software to generate maps has also been conceived and implemented alongside proprietary tools like ArcGIS.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] As a result, the barrier to entry for serving maps on the web has been lowered.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The terms *web GIS* and *web mapping* are often used interchangeably, but the terms are distinct.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web GIS uses and enables web maps, and end users who are *web mapping* are gaining analytical capabilities from Web GIS, however Web GIS has more applications than web mapping, and web mapping can be accomplished without Web GIS.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web GIS emphasizes geodata processing aspects more involved with design aspects such as data acquisition and server software architecture such as data storage and algorithms, than it does the end-user reports themselves.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The term *location-based services* refers to *web mapping* consumer goods and services.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping usually involves a web browser or other user agent capable of client-server interactions.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Questions of quality, usability, social benefits, and legal constraints are driving its evolution.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] A first classification of web maps has been made by Kraak in 2001.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] He distinguished *static* and *dynamic* web maps and further distinguished *interactive* and *view only* web maps.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Today there is an increased number of dynamic web maps types, and static web map sources.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The geodata can be a static provision, or need updates.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The borderline between analytical web maps and web GIS is fuzzy.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Parts of the analysis can be carried out by the GIS geodata server.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] As web clients gain capabilities processing is distributed.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Realtime maps show the situation of a phenomenon in close to realtime (only a few seconds or minutes delay).
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Data is collected by sensors and the maps are generated or updated at regular intervals or on demand.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Animated maps show changes in the map over time by animating one of the graphical or temporal variables.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Technologies enabling client-side display of animated web maps include scalable vector graphics (SVG), Adobe Flash, Java, QuickTime, and others.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web maps with real-time animation include weather maps, traffic congestion maps and vehicle monitoring systems.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] CartoDB launched an open source library, Torque, which enables the creation of dynamic animated maps with millions of records.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Twitter uses this technology to create maps to reflect how users reacted to news and events worldwide.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Collaborative maps are a developing potential.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] In proprietary or open source collaborative software, users collaborate to create and improve the web mapping experience.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This type of web mapping is the most popular or familiar amongst the population today.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Online atlases are collections of maps in a specific period of time like general reference maps, thematic maps, and geographical information.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The traditional atlas goes through a remarkably large transition when hosted on the web.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Atlases can cease their printed editions or offer printing on demand.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Some atlases also offer raw data downloads of the underlying geospatial data sources.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Static web pages are *view only* without animation or interactivity.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] These maps were often used before technological advancements allowed the user to interact.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] These files are created once, often manually, and infrequently updated.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Typical graphics formats for static web maps are PNG, JPEG, GIF, or TIFF (e.g., drg) for raster files, SVG, PDF or SWF for vector files.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] These include scanned paper maps not designed as screen maps.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Paper maps have a much higher resolution and information density than typical computer displays of the same physical size, and might be unreadable when displayed on screens at the wrong resolution.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Various companies now offer web mapping as a cloud based software as a service.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] These service providers allow users to create and share maps by uploading data to their servers (cloud storage).
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The maps are created either by using an in browser editor or writing scripts that leverage the service providers API's.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques, mapping software has many advantages.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This section contains some of the milestones of web mapping, online mapping services and atlases.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping technologies require both server-side and client-side applications.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The following is a list of technologies utilized in web mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web maps have become an essential tool for many, as illustrated by a 2021 labor strike demanding (among other things) a certain type of map.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping has allowed for a more environmentally conscious way of navigating location.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] With the creation of web mapping, people do not have to use paper maps anymore, as it is accessible through the internet, benefiting the environment.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Also, atlases or paper maps can become outdated as time passes and the relevant geography changes.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] With web mapping, users are able to access periodically updated geographical information to get step by step directions to a location based on where they currently are located.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Directions provided by web maps can allows be customised based on mode of transportation, with final distances and estimated travel times for each calculated beforehand.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Another benefit is that web mapping has allowed more of the general population to navigate around otherwise brand new areas because it is free and accessible to anyone with an internet connection.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Most web maps give real-time updates about traffic and road conditions, allowing drivers to make quicker and safer journeys.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Although a niche function, web mapping can be used to learn more about culture and history.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Users can explore historical maps, cultural landmarks, natural features, parks, trails, report issues, natural hazards, pollution, and much more.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] As much as web mapping has helped simplify our lives, there are also negative social consequences to the use of web mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] There have been concerns raised about the privacy of personal information while using web mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] It allows government agencies to create massive databases on individuals and their behaviors while the private sector keeps records of personal information.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This issue continues to be challenged and negotiated as web mapping has become more relevant.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] As the use of web mapping has increased, so has the amount of distractions while driving.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Drivers can alter their focus away from the road to their device very easily, which could result in a multitude of negative social consequences and safety concerns.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] While there are many benefits to web mapping allowing anyone to access, create, and distribute maps, many have raised ethical concerns.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The web facilitates the spread of misinformation, and people without strong understanding of cartography can publish seemingly authoritative products that may mislead the public.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This saw significant attention during the COVID-19 pandemic, where the prevalence of improper maps on dashboards contributed to the infodemic.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web maps require the internet to host, so they are subject to link rot, making information inaccessible.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Unlike physical maps, this can have major impacts on the historical record if the web map is the only source for the data it presents.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping is also used in geography games, notably of which is GeoGuessr.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] A popular browser based game, users are shown an image from Google Street View and must guess the location.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] The game was received with success upon its launch in May 2013, and skyrocketed to viral popularity during the COVID-19 pandemic as many content creators streamed themselves playing it.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping allows you to choose a route of travel with provided directions and real time traffic and road condition updates.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Of course, this is only possible with an internet connection.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Populations that are associated with lower incomes may not have access to a mobile device with internet as they may not be able to afford it, limiting them of this resource.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This technology might also be limiting to certain generations, as well.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Younger generations have been cultured in technology for the majority of their lives, so web mapping is an easy resource for them to use.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] However, older generations tend to be less efficient with technology, as it was not around for the majority of their lifetimes.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This can make it difficult for the older generation to understand how to use web mapping when planning their travels.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] They will often resort to paper maps or a GPS, as that is what is comfortable to them, even though those resources are less efficient and are more outdated than web mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] As web mapping has become more advanced, they have added a walking feature.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This has created an opportunity for the population who might not have access to and/or afford to have a car.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] They are still able to take advantage of this technology to get to a destination by foot.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping has also opened up new possibilities to those who might struggle with a vision disorder.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] More than a quarter of the world's population (about 2.2 billion people) suffer from vision impairment.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping has accommodated this large population by adding a speaking feature.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] When you enter a destination, you can turn your volume on and the maps will speak your directions to you.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This is not only convenient for visually impaired people, but also helps limit distractions while navigating.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] There have been concerns raised about the privacy and confidentiality of personal information while using web mapping.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web maps contain personal information such as locations, identities, or attributes of people, places, or things.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] If not properly secured, your information can be accessed, copied, or manipulated by unauthorized parties.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] This allows government agencies to create massive databases on individuals and their behaviors while the private sector keeps records of personal information.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] It can also lead to privacy breaches, data loss, or legal liabilities.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] To prevent these issues from happening, mostly in a work setting, you need to encrypt your data, use secure protocols and servers, and apply access control and authentication mechanisms.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Another possible barrier created by web mapping that may challenge web map security is data integrity and quality.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web maps rely entirely on data sources that could potentially be inaccurate, outdated, or corrupted.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] If the data is not verified and updated regularly, it can affect the reliability of the web maps.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] Web mapping can also be vulnerable to data tempering, spoofing, or injection attacks, where false or harmful data can be inserted into web maps.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] There may also be less threatening situations like when web maps may not be updated on a crash or traffic conditions, or may not take you on the most efficient route.
[src:openstreetmap/web-mapping] To prevent more of these issues from happening, it is important to report unsafe road conditions or any limitations or uncertainties of any web mapping features.
